You can cast the data as a char (byte) array then send it with the same command you are using to send your string &quot;S2 terminal for Bluetooth&quot;.

So currently you&#39;re doing something like Serial.write(&quot;S2 terminal for Bluetooth&quot;);

You can send multiple pieces of information using a (packed) struct. Packed means there are no extra bytes inserted by the compiler for alignment.

    typedef struct {
        int data_num_a;
        int data_num_b;
        char[32] data_str_c;
        char[32] data_str_d;
    } __attribute__((__packed__))data_msg_t;


So here is how you would send data using this:

    data_msg_t my_message;
    my_message.data_num_a = 1234;
    my_message.data_num_b = 5678;
    memcpy(my_message.data_str_c, &quot;String of up to 32 characters&quot;, 32);
    memcpy(my_message.data_str_d, &quot;other string&quot;, 32);
    
    Serial.write((char*)&amp;my_message, sizeof(my_message));

